<paragraph blockId="11.[113,647,692,1193]" box="[113,213,692,718]" pageId="11" pageNumber="526">REMARKS</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[113,647,692,1193]" pageId="11" pageNumber="526">
The specimens examined agree with the redescription of this species by 
<bibRefCitation author="MCLAUGHLIN P. A." box="[282,487,754,781]" pageId="11" pageNumber="526" pagination="1 - 28" refId="ref12802" refString="MCLAUGHLIN P. A. 2004. - Paguristes puniceus Henderson, 1896 (Decapoda: Anomura: Paguroidea: Diogenidae): a study in intraspecific variability. Zootaxa 742: 1 - 28." type="journal article" year="2004">McLaughlin (2004)</bibRefCitation>
. Some variation in the morphological characters not mentioned by 
<bibRefCitation author="MCLAUGHLIN P. A." box="[113,331,818,844]" pageId="11" pageNumber="526" pagination="1 - 28" refId="ref12802" refString="MCLAUGHLIN P. A. 2004. - Paguristes puniceus Henderson, 1896 (Decapoda: Anomura: Paguroidea: Diogenidae): a study in intraspecific variability. Zootaxa 742: 1 - 28." type="journal article" year="2004">McLaughlin (2004)</bibRefCitation>
were observed. The dorsolateral surfaces of the shields of the specimens from 
<collectingCountry box="[113,240,881,907]" name="Madagascar" pageId="11" pageNumber="526">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
have prominent spines. The antennal peduncles have more spines: the second segments of the antennal peduncles each have the dorsodistal angle produced, terminating into two large spines followed by three or four spines on the lateral margin, the dorsomesial distal angle has two prominent spines; the antennal acicles have six or seven spines on the mesial margin, and two to four spines on lateral margin. The chelipeds and the second and third pereopods are more setose.
</paragraph>
